---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About"
	description="Software designer and architect — from system-level programming to cloud-native applications. Building open source tools that prioritise offline-first operation, deterministic behaviour, and privacy by design."
	pubDate={new Date('2024-01-01')}
>
	<p>
		I'm a software designer and architect with 10+ years of experience building scalable platforms,
		analytics tools, and extensible architectures.
	</p>

	<p>
		Personally I'm focusing on tools that feel noticeably different from what already exists.
		I prioritise offline-first operation, deterministic behaviour, and privacy by design —
		software that works without depending on a network, a vendor, or a black box.
		My current projects:
	</p>

	<ul>
		<li>
			<strong><a href="https://dominikj111.github.io/engram/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Engram</a></strong> — A deterministic reasoning kernel — symbolic AI, a finite state machine, with configurable boundaries and self-improving weights.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong><a href="https://github.com/dominikj111/Weaver-Desktop" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Weaver Desktop</a></strong> — A lightweight desktop environment for embedded Linux and SBCs. Thin UI client — delegates all system operations to system daemon.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong><a href="https://github.com/dominikj111/JigsawFlow" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">JigsawFlow Microkernel</a></strong> — A Capability-Driven Architecture for Offline-First, Hot-Swappable, Language-Agnostic Applications.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<p>
		My interests pull in a few directions that end up reinforcing each other: programming techniques,
		artificial intelligence, neural networks, robotics, evolutionary patterns, parallel computing, and cognitive science.
		What ties them together is a curiosity about systems that adapt, reason, and operate independently —
		which is exactly what draws me to the projects above.
	</p>

	<p>
		Mathematics is a constant thread through all of it. I'm drawn to the areas that deal in precision and
		structure — graph theory, automata theory, computability theory, and probability theory with combinatorics.
		There's something satisfying about a result that is exactly right, not approximately right.
		I have little patience for numerical solutions to problems that have an analytic answer —
		approximation belongs in simulations and exploratory research, not in a final result where
		the real answer exists and is waiting to be found.
		The similar instinct shows up in hardware: tinkering with Arduino and Raspberry Pi is where
		theory meets physical constraint, and where the gap between the best solution and a
		good-enough one becomes impossible to ignore.
	</p>

	<div class="pf-callout">
		<p>
			Almost everything I know I learned from <strong>open sources</strong> — documentation, libraries, articles, projects
			people shared freely. A few books aside, I never paid for that knowledge.
			<strong>Open source</strong> wasn't just a convenience; it was the entire foundation.
			I've seen it work, consistently, across decades — and that's why giving back the same way feels
			less like a choice and more like the obvious thing to do.
			Everything I build and publish is free and <strong>open source</strong>, for anyone to use, learn from, or build on.
		</p>
		<p style="margin-top: 25px">
			I care about personal computing sovereignty. The direction most software is heading —
			cloud-dependent, always-online, vendor-locked — runs counter to how I think tools should work.
			Resilience and offline-first design aren't constraints; they're a statement about who the software
			serves.
			Rust crates on <a href="https://crates.io/users/dominikj111" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer me">crates.io</a>,
			utilities on <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/~domino2" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer me">npm</a>,
			and everything else on <a href="https://github.com/dominikj111" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer me">GitHub</a>.
		</p>
	</div>

	<p>
		<a
			class="pf-bmc-link"
			href="https://buymeacoffee.com/dominikj111"
			target="_blank"
			rel="noopener noreferrer"
		>
			☕ Buy me a coffee
		</a>
	</p>
</Layout>

